Yes, D3D11 has an interface to set the line width before drawing a line. The interface is called ID3D11DeviceContext and specifically, the Draw method with primitive topology set to D3D11_PRIMITIVE_TOPOLOGY_LINELIST or D3D11_PRIMITIVE_TOPOLOGY_LINESTRIP.

To set the line width, you need to create a rasterizer state object with the desired line width value and set it as the current rasterizer state before calling the Draw method. Here is an example of how to create a rasterizer state with a line width of 2.0:

```C++
D3D11_RASTERIZER_DESC rasterizerDesc = {};
rasterizerDesc.FillMode = D3D11_FILL_SOLID;
rasterizerDesc.CullMode = D3D11_CULL_NONE;
rasterizerDesc.DepthClipEnable = true;
rasterizerDesc.AntialiasedLineEnable = true;
rasterizerDesc.MultisampleEnable = true;
rasterizerDesc.ScissorEnable = false;
rasterizerDesc.SlopeScaledDepthBias = 0.0f;
rasterizerDesc.DepthBias = 0;

rasterizerDesc.FillMode = D3D11_FILL_SOLID;

// Set line width to 2.0f
rasterizerDesc.AntialiasedLineEnable = TRUE;
rasterizerDesc.MultisampleEnable = TRUE;
rasterizerDesc.DepthClipEnable = TRUE;
rasterizerDesc.CullMode = D3D11_CULL_BACK;

rasterizerDesc.FrontCounterClockwise = false;
rasterizerDesc.ScissorEnable = false;
rasterizerDesc.SlopeScaledDepthBias = 0.0f;
rasterizerDesc.DepthBias = 0;

ID3D11RasterizerState* rasterizerState;
device->CreateRasterizerState(&rasterizerDesc, &rasterizerState);

// Set the rasterizer state with the desired line width value
deviceContext->RSSetState(rasterizerState);

// Draw the line(s)
deviceContext->Draw(lineCount, vertexOffset);
```

