```js
import React, { useState } from "react";

function App() {
  const [color, setColor] = useState("#ffffff"); // initial white color
  const [imageUrl, setImageUrl] = useState(""); // empty initial image URL

  const handleColorClick = () => {
    const newColor = getRandomColor();
    setColor(newColor);
  };

  const handleImageClick = async () => {
    const response = await fetch("https://api.thecatapi.com/v1/images/search");
    const data = await response.json();
    const imageUrl = data[0].url;
    setImageUrl(imageUrl);
  };

  const getRandomColor = () => {
    const letters = "0123456789ABCDEF";
    let color = "#";
    for (let i = 0; i < 6; i++) {
      color += letters[Math.floor(Math.random() * 16)];
    }
    return color;
  };

  return (
    <div style={{ backgroundColor: color, height: "100vh" }}>
      <button onClick={handleColorClick}>Change Color</button>
      <button onClick={handleImageClick}>Get Cat Image</button>
      <br />
      {imageUrl && <img src={imageUrl} alt="Random cat" />}
    </div>
  );
}

export default App;
```

In this updated example, we're defining a new state variable `imageUrl` to keep track of the current cat image URL. We're also defining a new function `handleImageClick` that fetches a random cat image URL from the Cat API and sets it as the new `imageUrl` state using the `setImageUrl` function. We're then rendering an `img` element if `imageUrl` is not empty.

We're also rendering a second `button` that triggers the `handleImageClick` function when clicked. Note that we're using the `fetch` function to make a GET request to the Cat API endpoint and the `async/await` keywords to handle the asynchronous response.

